ttempted to understand, one way or another, the distinctive pathologies of the modern age. But every one also attempted to envision—if only through the faintest of traces, traces of mutual recognition, traces of another way of looking and seeing—the prospects for a radically different lifeworld. The world, after all, inevitably reflects back to us the character, the reach and range, of our vision.In these provocative essays, the author draws on the language of hermeneutical phenomenology and at the same time refines phenomenology itself as a method of working with our experience and thinking critically about the culture in which we live.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAppearance (Philosophy). 0aPhilosophy, Modern. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh  aaesthetic theory.  abenjamin.  acultural criticism.  adescartes.  aedmund husserl.  aemmanuel levinas.  aenlightenment.  aethics.  afriedrich nietzsche.  aheidegger.  ahistorical materialism.  ahuman experience.  ahusserl.  aintentionality.  alevinas.  amartin heidegger.  amaurice merleau-ponty.  amerleau-ponty.  amodes of perception.  amoral character.  amorality.  amutual recognition.  anatural philosophy.  anietzsche.  anihilism.  aocularcentrism.  aperspectivism.  aphenomenology.  aphilosophy.  apolitics.  aprivileging of vision.  arene descartes.  awalter benjamin.  awittgenstein.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000z97831106353480 cprintz978052021780540uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520922563?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520922563423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520922563/original  a978-3-11-063534-8  University of California Press Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  a